We consider a multiuser OFDM system with $N$ subcarriers where each user is assigned a subset of these subcarriers. Let $\mathbf{S}\in\{0,1\}^{N\times N}$ be a sparse matrix whose $(i,j)$th element is one if user $i$ is assigned the $j$th subcarrier and zero otherwise. We assume that the number of users is less than the total number of available subcarriers so that some of the subcarriers are unassigned. Furthermore, we let $\mathbf{A}=[\alpha_{ij}]\in\mathbb{R}^{N\times N}$ be a diagonal matrix with nonnegative real values $\alpha_{ii}$. Then, the received signal at the $n$th subcarrier of the $i$th user can be expressed as
\begin{equation*}
y_i[n] = \sum_{m=1}^M s_{im}a_{mn} x_m[n]+w_i[n],
\end{equation*}
where $x_m[n]$ is the transmitted symbol from the $m$th user at the $n$th subcarrier, $w_i[n]\sim\mathcal{CN}(0,\sigma^2)$ is additive white Gaussian noise, and $M=\text{rank}(\mathbf{S})$. Note that the entries of $\mathbf{S}$ determine which subcarriers are assigned to which users. In particular, if $s_{ij}=1$, then the $j$th subcarrier is assigned to the $i$th user. Otherwise, the $j$th subcarrier is unassigned. For simplicity, we focus on the case where all users have the same number of assigned subcarriers, i.e., $M=N$. This assumption can be relaxed by extending the definition of $\mathbf{S}$ to include additional columns corresponding to the unassigned subcarriers.

